	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Shonumi</b> [ Mon Jul 27, 2015 7:01 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: Gameboy Display Craziness</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It's actually a more subtle issue that highlights some specific (but small) differences in Game Boy models. DMG units initialize various parts of I/O (0xFF00 - 0xFF7F) with values of 0xFF. This happens as soon as the unit powers up, before the Boot ROM even starts. The OBP0 and OBP1 registers on the DMG are therefore already set (note: the neither the DMG nor the GBC Boot ROM even write to them). On the other hand, GBC and GBA units zero out these portions of I/O, so when running your program on these systems, you have to manually set OBP0 and OBP1.<br /><br />You'll find that BGB doesn't display your ball either when you set the system to Game Boy Color. If you open it up in debugging mode, you can see which values in I/O are 0xFF or 0x0 depending on the emulated system type. So the lesson here is to initialize everything and never rely on hardware to have done things ahead of time <img src="./images/smilies/icon_razz.gif" alt=":P" title="Razz" />

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


